1 (B) water quality models indicate that Vermont watersheds contribute
2 a significant majority of the annual phosphorus loading to the lake with
3 116,216 pounds of the total annual load of 151,314 pounds of phosphorus
4 originating in Vermont.
5 (5) Vermont has drafted and begun implementation of a Total Maximum
6 Daily Load plan to address impairment of Lake Memphremagog, and the
7 Agency of Natural Resources has committed to improving water quality in the
8 lake, but more action, attention, and funding is necessary to improve the health
9 of Lake Memphremagog as soon as possible.
10 (6) The General Assembly should declare Lake Memphremagog a lake
11 in crisis and dedicate additional time, money, and action to improve the lake’s
12 water quality as soon as possible to avoid continued threats to the natural
13 resources, drinking water, recreation, and economic benefits provided by the
14 lake.
15 Sec. 2. DECLARATION; LAKE MEMPHREMAGOG; LAKE IN CRISIS
16 Notwithstanding 10 V.S.A. § 1310, the General Assembly declares Lake
17 Memphremagog as a lake in crisis under 10 V.S.A. chapter 47, subchapter 2A.
18 The crisis response plan for Lake Memphremagog shall include controls limits
19 on discharges of effluent to tributaries of the lake.
